## Context
Ticket 0182 fortified the manuscript claim (A.1 tripod / A.5) that the
three pre-2007 intellectual traditions were structurally separate. The
worry was low power: the pre-2007 co-citation graph is the sparsest slice
of the corpus (coverage diagnostic: 1344 works, only 30% carry any
outgoing edge, median references per work = 0, grey literature 2/1344),
so co-citation would show separation almost regardless. A degree-
preserving configuration-model null rules this out:

- Induced tradition subgraph: 84 nodes (pricing 33, cdm 32, unfccc 19),
  369 edges.
- Within-tradition co-citation share: observed 0.889 vs null 0.374 ± 0.020
  (z = 25.9, empirical p = 0.001, N = 1000, seed 42).
- 3-partition modularity: observed 0.554 vs null -0.012 ± 0.020
  (z = 28.4, p = 0.001).

The observed separation exceeds the sparsity-conditioned null by ~26 sd.
Verdict FORTIFIED: the separation is a real intellectual boundary, not an
artefact of thin indexing. This ticket writes that one result into A.5.

